ba4_questions = [
  ("ba400000-0001-0001-0000-000000000001","ba400000-0001-0001-0000-000000000000","mcq",1,"A management accountant is asked to prepare a report that they know contains misleading information. Which fundamental principle is MOST directly threatened?","Integrity",'["Confidentiality","Professional Behaviour","Integrity","Objectivity"]',"Integrity requires being straightforward and honest. Knowingly preparing misleading information directly breaches integrity."),
  ("ba400000-0001-0001-0000-000000000002","ba400000-0001-0001-0000-000000000000","mcq",2,"An accountant has worked with the same client for 15 years and is close friends with the finance director. This creates which threat?","Familiarity threat",'["Self-interest threat","Advocacy threat","Intimidation threat","Familiarity threat"]',"Familiarity threat arises when a close relationship leads to over-sympathy, inadequate scrutiny, or prioritising the client's interests over professional obligations."),
  ("ba400000-0001-0001-0000-000000000003","ba400000-0001-0001-0000-000000000000","true_false",3,"The CIMA Code of Ethics is rules-based, requiring specific compliance with detailed rules for every situation.","False",None,"The CIMA Code of Ethics is PRINCIPLE-based, not rules-based. It requires members to exercise professional judgement in applying the fundamental principles."),
  ("ba400000-0001-0001-0000-000000000004","ba400000-0001-0001-0000-000000000000","mcq",4,"An accountant is reviewing financial statements that they themselves prepared last year. This is an example of:","Self-review threat",'["Self-interest threat","Self-review threat","Familiarity threat","Advocacy threat"]',"Self-review threat occurs when an accountant evaluates or audits their own previous work. Objectivity is compromised."),
  ("ba400000-0001-0002-0000-000000000001","ba400000-0001-0002-0000-000000000000","mcq",1,"Under UK law, a whistleblowing disclosure is MOST likely to receive legal protection if:","The employee believes in good faith it is in the public interest",'["It is made directly to the national press","The employee believes in good faith it is in the public interest","The employee has proof of the wrongdoing","It involves a minor regulatory breach"]',"The Public Interest Disclosure Act 1998 requires a genuine, good-faith belief that the disclosure is in the public interest. Proof is not required."),
  ("ba400000-0001-0002-0000-000000000002","ba400000-0001-0002-0000-000000000000","mcq",2,"What should an accountant do FIRST when facing a potential ethical conflict at work?","Gather the relevant facts and clearly identify the ethical issue",'["Immediately contact the external auditors","Gather the relevant facts and clearly identify the ethical issue","Resign to avoid being implicated","Report to the financial regulator"]',"The first step in CIMA's ethical conflict resolution framework is to gather facts and identify the nature of the ethical issue."),
  ("ba400000-0001-0002-0000-000000000003","ba400000-0001-0002-0000-000000000000","true_false",3,"An accountant who makes a protected disclosure can be legally dismissed by their employer for doing so.","False",None,"PIDA 1998 specifically protects whistleblowers from unfair dismissal and workplace detriment. Dismissing an employee for a qualifying protected disclosure is automatically unfair."),
  ("ba400000-0001-0002-0000-000000000004","ba400000-0001-0002-0000-000000000000","mcq",4,"An accountant's manager instructs them to overstate revenue to meet a bonus target. The most appropriate FIRST action is to:","Refuse and document the request; discuss the concern with the manager or seek guidance",'["Comply — the manager takes responsibility","Immediately report to the external auditor","Refuse and document the request; discuss the concern with the manager or seek guidance","Resign immediately"]',"The accountant should refuse, document the instruction, and attempt to resolve internally first. Immediately going external skips internal escalation steps."),
  ("ba400000-0002-0001-0000-000000000001","ba400000-0002-0001-0000-000000000000","mcq",1,"The agency problem in corporate governance arises from:","The separation of ownership from control, where managers may not act in shareholders' interests",'["External auditors acting in their own interest","The separation of ownership from control, where managers may not act in shareholders interests","Government regulation of company directors","Too many shareholders having conflicting objectives"]',"The agency problem arises because directors (agents) control the company on behalf of shareholders (principals). Directors may pursue personal benefits rather than maximising shareholder value."),
  ("ba400000-0002-0001-0000-000000000002","ba400000-0002-0001-0000-000000000000","mcq",2,"The UK Corporate Governance Code applies on a:","Comply or explain basis — companies must comply or give reasons why not",'["Mandatory compliance basis — all companies must follow it","Comply or explain basis — companies must comply or give reasons why not","Voluntary basis — companies can choose whether to follow it","Regulatory basis — enforced by the FCA with fines"]',"The UK Corporate Governance Code is not legally binding. Premium-listed companies must disclose whether they have complied, and if not, must explain their reasons."),
  ("ba400000-0002-0001-0000-000000000003","ba400000-0002-0001-0000-000000000000","true_false",3,"Executive directors should serve on the remuneration committee to ensure appropriate pay levels are set.","False",None,"Executive directors should NOT sit on the remuneration committee — they have a conflict of interest in setting their own pay. The committee must consist exclusively of independent NEDs."),
  ("ba400000-0002-0001-0000-000000000004","ba400000-0002-0001-0000-000000000000","mcq",4,"Which of the following best describes the purpose of the audit committee?","To oversee financial reporting, internal controls, and auditor relationships",'["To prepare the annual financial statements","To manage day-to-day financial operations","To oversee financial reporting, internal controls, and auditor relationships","To set the external auditors fees"]',"The audit committee oversees: integrity of financial statements, internal control and risk management systems, external auditor relationship, and internal audit function."),
  ("ba400000-0002-0002-0000-000000000001","ba400000-0002-0002-0000-000000000000","mcq",1,"A company purchases insurance for its warehoused stock against fire damage. This is an example of which risk response?","Transfer",'["Terminate","Tolerate","Transfer","Treat"]',"Insurance transfers the financial consequences of the risk to the insurer. The company still faces the risk of fire, but the financial impact is transferred."),
  ("ba400000-0002-0002-0000-000000000002","ba400000-0002-0002-0000-000000000000","mcq",2,"Requiring different employees to authorise purchases, receive goods, and approve payment is an example of:","Segregation of duties",'["Segregation of duties","Authorisation control","Physical control","Detective control"]',"Segregation of duties ensures no single person controls all stages of a transaction, making fraud much harder to commit and conceal."),
  ("ba400000-0002-0002-0000-000000000003","ba400000-0002-0002-0000-000000000000","true_false",3,"Internal controls can provide absolute assurance that an organisation will achieve its objectives.","False",None,"Internal controls can only provide REASONABLE assurance — not absolute. Limitations include human error, collusion, management override, and cost-benefit trade-offs."),
  ("ba400000-0002-0002-0000-000000000004","ba400000-0002-0002-0000-000000000000","mcq",4,"A bank reconciliation performed monthly is an example of which type of control?","Detective control",'["Preventive control","Detective control","Corrective control","Directive control"]',"Bank reconciliations detect errors and discrepancies after they have occurred. Preventive controls stop errors from occurring in the first place."),
  ("ba400000-0003-0001-0000-000000000001","ba400000-0003-0001-0000-000000000000","mcq",1,"Party A offers to sell goods for £1,000. Party B replies 'I'll take them for £900.' Which is correct?","Party B has made a counter-offer, rejecting A's original offer",'["A binding contract is formed at £900","Party B has made a counter-offer, rejecting As original offer","The original offer remains open for A to accept","Party B has made a valid acceptance with a modification"]',"A counter-offer is a rejection of the original offer and a new offer in its place. The original offer is destroyed."),
  ("ba400000-0003-0001-0000-000000000002","ba400000-0003-0001-0000-000000000000","mcq",2,"A product displayed on a supermarket shelf with a price label is:","An invitation to treat — not a binding offer",'["An offer that customers can accept at the checkout","An invitation to treat — not a binding offer","A guarantee of supply at that price","A contract formed when the customer picks up the item"]',"Goods on a shelf are an invitation to treat (Pharmaceutical Society of GB v Boots Cash Chemists [1953]). The customer makes the offer by presenting goods at the checkout."),
  ("ba400000-0003-0001-0000-000000000003","ba400000-0003-0001-0000-000000000000","true_false",3,"Consideration in a contract must always be money.","False",None,"Consideration is 'something of value' — but it does not have to be money. It can be goods, services, or a promise to do (or refrain from doing) something."),
  ("ba400000-0003-0001-0000-000000000004","ba400000-0003-0001-0000-000000000000","mcq",4,"Which remedy is most appropriate when a buyer breaches a contract for the sale of a unique, irreplaceable painting?","Specific performance — court orders the buyer to complete the purchase",'["Damages — financial compensation for loss","Specific performance — court orders the buyer to complete the purchase","Rescission — the contract is unwound","Injunction — prevents the seller from selling elsewhere"]',"Specific performance is available where damages would be an inadequate remedy — typically for unique goods (land, specific antiques, art)."),
  ("ba400000-0003-0002-0000-000000000001","ba400000-0003-0002-0000-000000000000","mcq",1,"The principle established in Salomon v Salomon [1897] states that:","A company is a legal person separate from its shareholders",'["Directors are personally liable for all company debts","A company is a legal person separate from its shareholders","Shareholders can always be sued for company obligations","Companies must have at least two shareholders"]',"Salomon v Salomon is the foundation of company law. Even a one-person company is a separate legal entity — it can own property, enter contracts, and be sued in its own name."),
  ("ba400000-0003-0002-0000-000000000002","ba400000-0003-0002-0000-000000000000","mcq",2,"Under the Companies Act 2006, a director must promote the success of the company for the benefit of:","The shareholders as a whole in the long term",'["The directors collectively","The shareholders as a whole in the long term","All stakeholders including employees, suppliers and creditors equally","The majority shareholder"]',"s.172 CA 2006 requires directors to act in good faith to promote long-term success for the benefit of members (shareholders) as a whole."),
  ("ba400000-0003-0002-0000-000000000003","ba400000-0003-0002-0000-000000000000","mcq",3,"An employee is dismissed without notice after 3 months. They have no unfair dismissal claim, but may have a claim for:","Wrongful dismissal",'["Redundancy pay","Wrongful dismissal","Discrimination under the Equality Act","Statutory maternity pay"]',"Unfair dismissal requires 2 years' service. Wrongful dismissal is a breach of contract claim available from day 1 — applies when employer fails to give proper notice."),
  ("ba400000-0003-0002-0000-000000000004","ba400000-0003-0002-0000-000000000000","mcq",4,"Under the Bribery Act 2010, which offence can a company commit even if the bribery was by a third party without the company's knowledge?","Failure to prevent bribery by an associated person",'["Fraud by false representation","Failure to prevent bribery by an associated person","Fraud by abuse of position","Money laundering"]',"The Bribery Act 2010 s.7 creates strict liability: a company is guilty if an associated person pays a bribe on its behalf, unless the company had adequate anti-bribery procedures."),
]

